```class Solution {
public:
    bool reorderedPowerOf2(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n > 1) {
            if (n % 10 == 1 && count < 3) {
                return false;
            }
            n /= 10;
            count++;
        }
        return true;
    }
};```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(n))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:
The solution iterates through the digits of the number n using a while loop. Inside the loop, it checks if the last digit is 1 and the count of 1's is less than 3. If this condition is true, it means that the number is not a power of 2, so we return false. Otherwise, we increment the count and divide n by 10 to remove the last digit. This process continues until n becomes 0, indicating that the number is a power of 2. Finally, we return true. The time complexity is O(log(n)) due to the iterative approach, and the space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space. The energy implications are low as the algorithm has a negligible impact on energy consumption.

